Facial Emotion Detection

Problem Definition

  • David Antonio Ortega Alfaro

The context: Why is this problem important to solve?

From the problem statement we can see that facial recognition is important in order to correctly asess emotions conveyed by people, because as much as 55% of emotion is conveyed through facial expressions. The task of identifying said emotions is taxing and expenssive for analysts to manually categorize every photo. For this, we can use only some manual categorization and afterwards deploy a Neural Network which can easily categorize this emotions once trained.

This helps free up time for analysts to do other tasks and modernizes the enterprise's usage of technology, adding needed intelligence and categorization for whatever it's purpose may be.

The objectives: What is the intended goal?

From the Problem Statement: "to use Deep Learning and Artificial Intelligence techniques to create a computer vision model that can accurately detect facial emotions."

The key questions: What are the key questions that need to be answered?

  • Which is the model that best performs when categorizing this images?
  • What are the parameters which help this identification?
  • How can we apply this model to other aplications?

The problem formulation: What are we trying to solve using data science?

Solve a categorization problem of images using Deep Learning, specificallly computer vision neural networks, in this case, for classifying human emotions.

About the dataset

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

happy: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
sad: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
surprise: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
neutral: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

Model Building

Think About It:

  • Are Convolutional Neural Networks the right approach? Should we have gone with Artificial Neural Networks instead?

This is definitely a setup for a CNN, because it can detect local features like edges and is more efficient than a ANN, which would require massive computation to train for every pixel in the images.

  • What are the advantages of CNNs over ANNs and are they applicable here?

They are designed specifically for processing matrix data such as images. They use convolutional layers to detect spatial features like edges, corners, textures, and patterns, meaning they "slide" across an image to detect patterns, capturing local spatial relationships between pixels. This preserves the spatial structure of the data.

Creating the Base Neural Network

In[8]:
# In this case we will use the same approach used in the Elective project:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, LeakyReLU, MaxPooling2D, Flatten

def cnn_model_1():

    model = Sequential()
    # Load and convert into 2d the input shape
    model.add(Conv2D(16, (3, 3), padding='same', input_shape=(32, 32, 1)))
    # Hidden layers
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    # Second layer
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    # Poll observed data
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    # Return it into a one dimentional layer
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(32))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    # Output layer
    model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax')) # output of 4
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

cnn_model_1 = cnn_model_1()

# Now we follow with a max polling section, adding dropout layers and normalizing the data, this is the same model used during the elective part
# In that case it heavily improved prediction, hopefully it will do the same now
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, LeakyReLU, MaxPooling2D, Flatten


def cnn_model_2():
    model = Sequential()

    model.add(Conv2D(16, (3, 3), padding='same', input_shape=(32, 32, 3))) # changing the model so it takes RGB
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    # Early normalization to prevent drift
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(32))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    # Missing dropout layer
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(4, activation='softmax'))

    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

cnn_model_2 = cnn_model_2()

Transfer Learning Architectures

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images. Therefore, we need to create new DataLoaders.

Creating our Data Loaders for Transfer Learning Architectures

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network. We will have to go with color_mode = 'rgb' as this is the required format for the transfer learning architectures.

# Using the modell suggested in the Reference from the Low Code Option:

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, BatchNormalization, LeakyReLU, MaxPooling2D, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten, Dense, Activation
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

# Build the CNN model
def build_custom_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4):
    model = Sequential()

    # Block 1
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (2, 2), padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Block 2
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding='same', activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Block 3
    model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding='same', activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Block 4
    model.add(Conv2D(512, (2, 2), padding='same', activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Block 5
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (2, 2), padding='same', activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Fully Connected Layers
    model.add(Flatten())

    # Dense block 1
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Dense block 2
    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Output layer
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Instantiate the model
custom_cnn_model = build_custom_cnn()

**Observations and Insights: Worse than a simpler cnn model **

Conclusion: After testing a range of models it seems to be clear that complexity is not always the solution to solving classification problems. This is because classification problems in CNN networks rely on dpecific use cases in which testing several models is key. Using pretrained models seems like a good solution to these problems; but the specifities of said models affect heavily the outcomes of these; the way they were trained makes them fit for problems whose ressemblance to the training set is high. Using said models without the training weights result in the worst performance amongst the models, so it makes no sense using prebuilt structures without them. This being said, with the EfficientNet problem it seems like we could have struck gold, because of how well it performed on the training set; perhaps adding several dropout layers on top of it could help the final prediction.

Insights

Refined insights:

  • What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?

  • Classification of facial expressions is a problem which can be better solved using simpler CNN designs.

  • The input components are key to the problem, as such, we must use their initial features to the fullest extent. In this case BNW images as input we must generate the data in greyscales.

  • It is a complex problem, because facial expressions vary widely between human beings, from skin color to the shape of the mouth and teeth, as well as setting. Adding further images to the sets in more and more cases could help the model.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:

  • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?
  • Complexity =/= Better problem solving.
  • Use prebuilt models carefully, and only when their especifications help the building of the model.
  • The better performing model was the Second CNN we built for the Elective Project. Even so, it's accuracy being 70% in train and validation shows that ther is ample room for improvement.
  • The Efficient net model also shows impressive fitting, adding dropout layers could help it solve for the overfitting, but it is yet to be tested; I will do so for the final delivery.

Proposal for the final solution design:

  • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?
  • A two way strategy:
    • Build a CNN model simmilar to the best performing CNN built here, while adding and testing more for the hyperparameters.
    • Refine the architecture of the Efficient Net architecture adding dropout layers on top of it.
    • Try for higher resolutions in both cases.
